@inproceedings{WOS504,
abstract = {The native perennial Urtica dioica and the invasive alien annual Impatiens glandulifera often co-occur in European riparian herb communities. This paper aims to answer two questions: i) can l. glandulifera outcompete U. dioica: and ii) how does hydrology influence competition? Two mesocosm experiments assessed growth of, and competition between, the two species when subjected firstly to three water-table regimes and secondly to five flood treatments. Results indicated that both species preferred lower water-tables and that floods early in spring adversely affected their growth. Deposition of sediment during flooding appeared to have little effect. Presence of U. dioica appeared to inhibit germination and, in flooded treatments. growth of l. glandulifera. However, during the water-table experiment, U. dioica plants grown in mixed cultures with l. glandulifera showed significantly reduced growth at the end of season compared to those grown in monocultures. This indicates that. once established. l. glandulifera can have a negative effect on U. dioica. These results point to a rare case of an annual species, l. glandulifera, out-competing a perennial, U. dioica. They also have implications for the biodiversity and management of riparian habitats.},
